{
  "buggy_files": [
    "net/sunrpc/sched.c",
    "fs/nfs/inode.c"
  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "__rpc_execute",
    "__nfs_revalidate_inode"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.8,
  "reasoning": "The bug manifests as NFS mount disappearance during autofs mount expiration. Root cause is a race condition in signal handling: (1) During path lookup/mount expiration, nfs_lookup_revalidate triggers nfs_revalidate_inode which initiates an RPC getattr call; (2) The RPC task enters __rpc_execute and waits for the server reply (line 780-782 in net/sunrpc/sched.c via out_of_line_wait_on_bit with rpc_wait_bit_killable); (3) While the task is waiting, a signal (SIGKILL) is delivered to the task - this can happen during autofs unmount/shutdown processing; (4) The wait function rpc_wait_bit_killable detects the signal and returns -ERESTARTSYS; (5) __rpc_execute exits with -ERESTARTSYS (line 792) even though the server may have already sent the reply or be about to send it; (6) This error is returned to the NFS layer in __nfs_revalidate_inode (fs/nfs/inode.c line 960-970); (7) __nfs_revalidate_inode treats this as a permanent error (only special-casing -ESTALE at line 965) and propagates the error; (8) nfs_lookup_revalidate returns 0 (invalid) causing the dentry to be invalidated; (9) The autofs mount point becomes inaccessible and gets unmounted. The core issues are: (A) The RPC layer doesn't check if the reply has already been received before exiting with -ERESTARTSYS when a signal is detected; (B) The NFS layer doesn't handle -ERESTARTSYS specially - it should either retry the operation or not mark the inode as permanently invalid."
}

